english:
  title: 'Record of the Stone Bell at Sineullsa Temple: A Monument to the Reliquary of Pojae'
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When Pojae entered nirvana at Sineullsa Temple in Yeohung, miracles blazed forth. The doubtful found clarity, and the faithful grew ever more devoted. They resolved to kindle reverence for a thousand years hence, building a hall to enshrine his image and casting a bell to house his sacred relics—sparing no effort in their devotion.

    One called Gaeksin actually cast the stone bell, while another named Gaekju sought the finest stone to record these deeds. He came to me requesting these words:

    "The Hall of廉政 stands in Cheonnyeong, and our temple has hosted many visitors there. When Gaekju told the magistrate of this work, he replied with enthusiasm: 'When I journey to the capital, I shall surely ask Korean masters for a few words on behalf of the abbot—they will not refuse.' Would you, venerable sir, bestow your brush upon this?'"

    I answered: "The Pavilion of River and Moon was Pojae's dwelling place. Though his body has turned to ash, the river and moon remain as they were. Now Sineullsa overlooks the Yangtze, and the stone bell stands firm. When moonlight falls, its shadow dances upon the water—heaven's light, water's hue, lampglow and incense smoke all mingle there. This Pavilion of River and Moon, though ages pass like ink-black kalpas, will preserve Pojae's presence as if he still lived among us.

    Yet consider: Pojae's relics scatter to the four directions—some rest amid towering peaks in mist and cloud, others dwell in humble streets amid dust and smoke, some racing to heights, some settling in lowlands. Those who cherish them do so tenfold more faithfully than during his lifetime. How much more fitting that Gaekju tends these relics with devoted heart at the very place of his master's passing.

    Sineullsa, having been opened as a great dharma sanctuary by Pojae, shall endure eternally. The stone bell's solidity is not merely bound to Sineullsa's fate—it shall flow endless as this river and this moon itself.

    Alas, ephemeral flowers are not mere glimpses, ink-dark kalpas not merely spacious—such is the nature of things. Yet the world knows rise and fall. Though worlds may be born and destroyed, the human heart remains unchanging. Will Pojae's relics follow the world's cycles of creation and dissolution? Or will they abide with the human heart, eternal and unchanging? Even the simple-minded know which to choose.

    When those in ages to come reverence these relics, let them honor Pojae's noble spirit and seek it within their own hearts. Thus alone can they repay his grace. Otherwise, Pojae's way remains merely his own way—what concern is it of mine? Therefore this record is written."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Pavilion of River and Moon (江月軒): A reference to Pojae''s dwelling place, symbolizing how natural beauty and the sacred persist beyond individual mortality.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The stone bell (石鐘): Serves as both a literal artifact and a metaphor for permanence and the transmission of spiritual legacy.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Ink-dark kalpas (墨劫): In Buddhist cosmology, a kalpa is an immensely long period of time; the ''ink-dark'' suggests obscurity yet boundlessness.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The four directions: Represents the dispersal of relics throughout the world, a common practice in Buddhist tradition to spread blessings.'
